question: Before 1 July 2019, will the FAO report 1,200,000 or more pigs have been culled in China to thwart the spread of African Swine Fever?
rationale: 077d40c5cc6eac97b956a83b8c62343eb198aee1: Yes, 0.95 probability 077d40c5cc6eac97b956a83b8c62343eb198aee1: No, 0.050000000000000044 probability 077d40c5cc6eac97b956a83b8c62343eb198aee1: According to the current FAO report, 1,129,000 pigs have already been culled in China to stop the spread, and additional sources indicate that this number may already be under-reported. Although Chinese authorities claim the number of cases is dropping, many fear that the claims are a cover-up to avoid panic. The disease does not appear to be going away and has infected pigs throughout Asia and now Australia. Because there is no vaccine to prevent the disease, culling is currently the only way to stop it from spreading. Furthermore, the disease lives on contaminated materials for weeks, making it difficult to stop the spread. Some experts predict that up to 200 million pigs will be culled or die from the disease in China this year. Given the difficulty of stopping the spread of swine flu and the already large number of pigs that have been culled, I predict a very high chance that 1,200,000 or more pigs will be culled by July 1. https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/3002717/china-says-it-has-contained-african-swine-fever-cover-claims https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-swinefever-oie/china-faces-long-struggle-to-tackle-african-swine-fever-oie-idUSKCN1SY1SA

20b9406297a61d840e705f17738aef2f93589cff: Biological attacks are frowned upon by everyone in the world.  While any time of violent act is often responded to in a quick manner, biological attacks are highly frowned upon by all countries of power and often met with quick punishment to those who unleashed them.  These attacks are rare and most countries will not use them.  However, biological attacks are often cheap to make and deploy, so terror groups may look to them in some regard.  With this information in mind, I would say the chance of an attack is low, but it is always a possibility given how common terror attacks have been in the last 20 years.  According to CNN, the last chemical attack was in 2018, in Syria, but was quickly met with force the US and other countries.  There has not been another documented attack since then.  For these reasons, my prediction remains low.

question: Before 30 July 2019, will Norway's parliament approve legislation on the Government Pension Fund Global divesting from oil and gas companies?
rationale: 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Yes, 0.85 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: No, 0.15000000000000002 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Norway appears to be making a shift from fossil fuels and investing more in renewable energy companies: https://www.pionline.com/article/20190405/ONLINE/190409865/norway-sovereign-wealth-fund-doubles-permitted-allocation-to-renewable-energy-infrastructure. On April 5, it was announced that the Government Pension Fund Global would be allowed to invest up to $13.9 billion unlisted renewable energy infrastructure via segregated mandates. This is intended to be a small step in shifting assets from previous investments into "smaller" markets and assessing overall profitability of their ventures. It's important to understand that we won't see complete divestment from oil and gas, but that government is allowing the fund to seek alternatives in the near future. The change that occurred on April 5 does not guarantee that the fund will pursue renewable energy companies as their sole investment, rather that they can test the waters by investing them and seeing how profitable they are compared to keeping investments in the fossil fuel industry. [UPDATE:] 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Yes, 0.9 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: No, 0.09999999999999998 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Norway's divestment from oil-and-gas exploration and production companies has been planned for quite some time, and now the fund's management chief is stating that they may further increase their allocation to green bonds due to their low cost: https://www.ipe.com/news/costs/norways-oil-fund-eyes-bigger-green-bonds-allocation-low-cost-cited/www.ipe.com/news/costs/norways-oil-fund-eyes-bigger-green-bonds-allocation-low-cost-cited/10030794.fullarticle. However, divestment has not proceeded as smoothly as anticipated, largely due to how the fund assesses how fossil fuel companies should be evaluated for inclusion or exclusion in the fund. See: https://www.ipe.com/countries/norway/norway-clarifies-swfs-climate-rules-to-facilitate-exclusions/10030542.article. In further defining which criterion the fund uses to evaluate coal operations, we may see GPFG actually clinging to old investments for longer than initially expected.

question: Will Gotabaya Rajapaksa receive the most votes in the first round of the 2019 Sri Lankan presidential election?
rationale: 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: Yes, and he will win a majority of votes, 0.35 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: Yes, and he will win a plurality of votes, 0.15 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: No, 0.5 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: According to The Hindu (https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/op-ed/an-election-dilemma-in-sri-lanka/article29779146.ece), Gotabaya Rajapaksa was the early favorite in the presidential race and is currently one of two front runners to win the election. Rajapaksa has earned the support of the Buddhist community, the largest voting group in Sri Lanka. He also has the endorsement of many powerful and notable groups within the country and is a local favorite to many. However, a win in the Sri Lankan presidential election is still far from given. The thorn that remains in his side is his brother reputation which is still fresh in many voters' minds. Gotabaya Rajapaksa is the younger brother of the former highly controversial President Mahinda Rajapaksa. His brother served as president of Sri Lanka from 2005-2015 and has had allegations made against him ranging from rampant corruption to human rights abuses. The allegations made against him were very serious and many voters may be hesitant to put another Rajapaksa into power, despite his perceived popularity. If Rajapaksa loses, this is going to be the primary reason. His competitor, Sajith Premadasa, is definitely no push-over. According to another article by The Hindu (https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/sri-lanka-presidential-election-tna-endorses-sajith-premadasa/article29907481.ece), Premadasa just recently received an important endorsement by Sri Lanka's main Tamil party, the Tamil National Alliance. With this endorsement, Rajapaksa likely loses on a large proportion of the Tamil and Muslim minority group, which happens to make up a quarter of the electorate. In a tight contest, which this is exactly what we have, the Tamil and Muslim votes could be crucial in determining the winner of the election. With no other candidates really having much of a chance, the election comes down to Rajapaksa and Premadasa. At this point, the election is a coin-toss and either candidate has a chance of winning. With that said, Rajapaksa has a 50% chance of receiving the most votes. Should he in fact receive the most votes, he'll likely win by a majority instead of a plurality due to the fact that this is a two-person race.
answer_text: ['Yes, and he will win a majority of votes', 'Yes, and he will win a plurality of votes', 'No']

question: Before 30 July 2019, will Ukraine and Russia/Russian-backed separatists exchange prisoners?
rationale: 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: Yes, 0.1 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: No, 0.9 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: According to 112 International (https://112.international/ukraine-top-news/ukraine-to-demand-setting-date-of-prisoners-exchange-at-trilateral-contact-group-meeting-38004.html), Ukraine was planning to demand a setting date for prisoner exchange at the Trilateral Contact Group meeting back in March. Ukraine wanted to exchange 25 Russians convicted in Ukraine for Ukrainian political prisoners kept in Russia. Unfortunately, Russia is not too keen on this plan. According to the KyivPost (https://www.kyivpost.com/ukraine-politics/unian-ukraine-names-terms-of-swapping-25-russians-pardoning-72-separatists.html), Ukraine has attempted to sweeten the deal by claiming that it is "ready to hand over to Russia 25 Russian nationals and grant pardon to 72 militants in exchange for 19 civilians and soldiers held in Donbas". But, Russia has since ignored any requests or demands in connection to prisoner exchange. In fact, there has not been a successful prisoner exchange since 2017 between Russia and Ukraine. Based on these facts, it would be reasonable to assume that it would be very improbable that Ukraine and Russia would initiate a prisoner exchange before July 30, 2019. There has not been a successful exchange in over two years, and the fact that Russia is not responding to any requests is further proof that any type of prisoner exchange is highly unlikely at this point in time. [UPDATE:] 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: Yes, 0.15 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: No, 0.85 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: I am updating my previous forecast on prisoner exchange between Ukraine and Russia. Although, in recent news, there has been a presidential election in Ukraine and a new leader has been elected. According to The New York Times (https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/21/world/europe/Volodymyr-Zelensky-ukraine-elections.html), "The comedian Volodymyr Zelensky won a landslide victory in Ukraine's presidential election, according to official results with nearly all of the votes counted, making a comic actor with no experience in government or the military the commander in chief of a country that has been at war with Russian proxies for over five years". In addition, according to ABC News (https://abcnews.go.com/International/russian-officials-comedians-win-ukraine/story?id=62552468), Russian officials have expressed satisfaction at Poroshenko's defeat and optimism about Zelensky. "In a sign that Moscow hopes he will be easier to handle than Poroshenko, Russia's prime minister, Dmitry Medvedev, congratulated Zelensky on his victory and said he believed his election offered a chance for Ukraine and Russia to improve relations". Due to the fact that Ukraine has a new leader and Russia has expressed satisfaction with him, this may be a promising sign that relations between Ukraine and Russia may improve. With that said, the chances of a Ukraine/Russian prisoner exchange occurring may still be very unlikely, but the odds definitely have improved based on this news. My probability has been updated based on this new information on the Ukrainian election. [UPDATE:] 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: Yes, 0.25 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: No, 0.75 probability 0d23d2fff5295c18dc05ddeae13a82920eff629c: I am updating my previous forecast on prisoner exchange between Ukraine and Russia. Previously, I had explained that Russian officials had expressed satisfaction with the outcome of the Ukrainian election and that it had offered a chance for Ukraine and Russia to improve their relations. Although, despite these promising signs of improved relations, I explained that it was still rather unlikely that a Ukraine/Russian prisoner exchange would occur, especially since Russia was seemingly avoiding the topic. Since my last forecast, there have been new developments regarding a prisoner exchange. According to Urdupoint (https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/russia-hopes-discussion-of-prisoner-exchange-625558.html), Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov went on record to say that "Russia hopes that the discussion of the exchange of prisoners with Ukraine will continue". Also, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy, at his inauguration, said that he was ready for a dialogue between Ukraine and Russia to resolve the conflict occurring in Donbas, but that the first step would be the return of held prisoners. According to 112 International (https://112.international/politics/zelensky-calls-for-exchange-of-prisoners-in-all-to-all-format-39284.html), newly elected President Volodymyr Zelensky, called for an exchange of prisoners in "all-to-all" format. Zelensky went on to say that "I emphasize once again that I am ready for negotiations. I hope that at the next meeting in the Normandy format, Russia will demonstrate readiness for de-escalation. A concrete confirmation of this readiness should be the mutual exchange of our citizens in the "all-to-all" format. Without exceptions.". Based on this new information, it seems much more likely that a prisoner exchange could in fact occur before July 30. Both Russia and Ukraine have demonstrated that they are willing to discuss an exchange of prisoners, which is extremely promising. My probabilities have been updated to reflect this new information.

question: Before 30 July 2019, will the Afghan Taliban and the governments of Afghanistan and the United States hold official three-way peace talks?
rationale: 6360602f414290f311dc8f1c4bd9fabf82a57a22: Yes, 0.05 probability 6360602f414290f311dc8f1c4bd9fabf82a57a22: No, 0.95 probability 6360602f414290f311dc8f1c4bd9fabf82a57a22: While strides have somewhat been made between the US and the Taliban — particularly in the arena of counterterrorism initiatives — the possibility for formal, trilateral intra-Afghan peace talks involving the US are no more likely now than they were a year ago in my mind, and they are certainly not probable to happen in the near future. One month removed from an ostensibly productive 16-day negotiation in Katar, the Taliban dramatically announced a spring offensive -- which predictably follows a long line of excruciatingly similar aggressive posturing between the militant group and Afghan leadership. Moreover, in addition to the unproductive communication between the two groups within the country, there continues to be an equally predictable theme of conflict between US diplomats and the Ghani government— which remains indignant at the prospect of the US brokering deals with the Taliban at all. And, meanwhile, the resulting tensions only continue to escalate. This same pattern has been happening over and over again, for well over a year now. Barring a near paradigm shift in cooperation between the respective groups in Afghanistan, I just don't see trilateral peace talks happening by the end of July. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/12/world/asia/taliban-spring-offensive-afghanistan.html https://twitter.com/US4AfghanPeace/status/1116761194797391873

question: Will Hong Kong limit or ban cash withdrawals from banks between 19 September 2019 and 29 November 2019?
rationale:

15b184efd8c522294bf0cc1200bc304a86f4e6f2: A lot can happen in two months. With protests still in full swing, both sides will find new ways to antagonize the other. Right now the daily withdrawal limit stands at around $2,500 (US equivilent). What I find interesting is that the limit includes foreign currency. There are many ways the Hong Kong government could fulfill this scenario - they could limit or restrict the purchase or withdrawal of other currency to discourage migration during the protests. They could impose even minor limitations on current standard withdrawal rates. Of course, on the other side, they could maintain the current limits and use max withdrawals to identify protesters (or label anyone they want to as such...and therefore a threat to the state) it could go either way. They could also choose to impose a limit and then, after some short time, remove it as a gesture of "good faith" to make it seem like they are taking the situation seriously and feign bending to the will of the protesters. With so many ways to satisfy the scenario, I'm going out on a limb and saying it can truly go either way.

question: Will the WHO declare a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC) between 9 May 2019 and 15 July 2019?
rationale:

9b01b388135b88a8f9460ce97d0c52f3cddbcb10: The last declaration of a Public Health Emergency of International Concern was for the Zika virus in early 2016. Because an outbreak within a country's borders does not constitute an international emergency, it is highly unlikely that a PHEIC related to this issue will be declared in the next six weeks. In 2019, the only location reporting the Ebloa virus was the Democratic Republic of Congo. Measles, on the other hand, has crossed borders and has been reported in Tunisia, the Western Pacific Region, the European Region. On May 7, the WHO provided a disease outbreak update that read "a resurgence of measles cases has been seen in all WHO Regions." That said, they have not made a recommendation towards "compulsory vaccination, travel restrictions, or border screening for measles." The likelihood is low, but it seems that the possibility is on the higher end of low.

question: Will Hong Kong limit or ban cash withdrawals from banks between 19 September 2019 and 29 November 2019?
rationale: 66f8aaf95b42f131fe8c4875ec110ea8f91f18a6: Yes, 0.1 probability 66f8aaf95b42f131fe8c4875ec110ea8f91f18a6: No, 0.9 probability 66f8aaf95b42f131fe8c4875ec110ea8f91f18a6: As unrest continues in Hong Kong, protesters are trying a new tactic. Hong Kong protesters are calling for massive ATM withdrawals in an attempt to drain banks of currency as an economic warning to China. They hope that through so many cash withdrawals, it will force banks to run out of cash and to pressure the dollar's fixed exchange rate. Despite their attempt, Hong Kong banks have stated that they can easily handle the money withdrawals and that there is no concern about running out of bank notes. According to banks, ATM's already have a $20,000-$40,000 daily withdrawal limit, which is more than enough to prevent banks from running out of cash. question: Will there be more than 3,500 cumulative Ebola cases from the North Kivu Ebola Outbreak before 1 October 2019, according to the Humanitarian Data Exchange?
rationale: c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: Yes, 1.0 probability c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: No, 0.0 probability c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: Yes, unfortunately there have currently been about 2000 Ebola cases in this epidemic. Around the end of March 2019 (when there were only about 1000 cases), the rate of growth of Ebola cases noticeably increased. Although it appears that growth of the total number of cases has been slowed slightly, it is still growing at a rate of about 500 new cases per month. At this rate the cumulative total will surpass 3500 by 1 October 2019. https://data.humdata.org/dataset/ebola-cases-and-deaths-drc-north-kivu [UPDATE:] c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: Yes, 0.0 probability c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: No, 1.0 probability c79791501f1763fc7227f3862f0545ccc543c85a: On 3 August 2018, at the beginning of the North Kivu Ebola outbreak, there were 43 cases. As of 13 July 2019, there are 2489 cumulative cases (https://data.humdata.org/dataset/ebola-cases-and-deaths-drc-north-kivu/resource/4532a799-ebaf-4ff6-95a5-3607973f0de4). So, in a 344-day span, there has been an increase of roughly 2,446 in cumulative cases, or about 7.11 per day on average. There are an additional 80 days from 13 July to 1 October 2019, so if cases continue to increase at at least a linear rate, there will be about 3,058 (3,015+43) cumulative cases by 1 October. Alternatively, on 1 April 2019 (when the rate of cases appears to increase; see https://data.humdata.org/dataset/ebola-cases-and-deaths-drc-north-kivu) there were 1089 total cases, increasing by 1400 over a 103-day span. This comes out to about 13.59 new cases per day on average. If cases continue to increase at this rate, there will be about 3,576 (13.59*183 + 1089) cumulative cases by 1 October 2019. Since the rate of new cases has slowed down since June 2019, I have to conclude the cumulative number of cases will not reach 3,500 by October 2019.

Which isn't to say cholera isn't going to happen, but there are no DONs worldwide for cholera so far this year yet. March 2, 2018 is the last cholera DON for the Congo, with 2018 DONs in other African countries since then including Somalia, Cameroon, Algeria, Niger and Zimbabwe. I think there is a little less than 25% chance we'll see a DON for cholera in the Congo before 25 May 2019. Sources: https://www.who.int/csr/don/archive/year/2019/en/ https://www.who.int/csr/don/archive/year/2018/en/ https://www.who.int/csr/don/02-march-2018-cholera-drc/en/ [UPDATE:] 90e3624d2e06b1418cfa1a4943620b1736e103d4: Yes, 0.2 probability 90e3624d2e06b1418cfa1a4943620b1736e103d4: No, 0.8 probability 90e3624d2e06b1418cfa1a4943620b1736e103d4: I'm lowering my forecast slightly to 20% from last week. We've seen no cholera activity near or around the Congo recently and no cholera DONs in 2019 and none for the Congo itself since March 2, 2018. (Source: https://www.who.int/csr/don/archive/year/2019/en/ ) There is still the very real possibility though, as https://www.afro.who.int/news/whos-response-cholera-epidemic-democratic-republic-congo reports: "DRC has, from early 2016 to September, registered a cumulative total of 18.252 suspected cholera cases, of which 516 deaths (fatality rate of 2.8%) throughout the country, particularly in the Equateur, Kinshasa, Upper-Lomami, Upper-Katanga, Maï-Ndombe, Mongala, North-Kivu, Tshopo and South-Kivu Provinces."

South Korean officials revealed that Seoul would expedite its preparations to challenge the Japanese measures at the World Trade Organization, and also review whether to continue exchanging military information with Japan — a key element in the current tripartite security cooperation with the United States. question: Will the Government of Canada issue a travel advisory of "Exercise a high degree of caution," "Avoid non-essential travel," or "Avoid all travel" for New Zealand between 4 April 2019 and 12 June 2019?
rationale: 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Yes, 0.05 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: No, 0.95 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: The last updated travel advisory for New Zealand was listed on March 19, 2019 as "Take normal security precautions," and this is still valid on April 4, 2019. Mind you, this update came 4 days after the Christchurch terrorist attack that resulted in multiple deaths and injuries. It is important to understand that the Christchurch terrorist attack was opportunistic and took advantage of the country when law enforcement and the general public were complacent. Now that the entire country is on edge, the likelihood of follow-up attacks is minimal. New Zealand is considered a relatively safe country and it is unlikely that the Canadian government will adjust their travel advisory unless another terrorist incident were to occur in the near future. New Zealand's national terrorism threat level is still considered "High" by local government authorities: https://dpmc.govt.nz/our-programmes/national-security-and-intelligence/national-security/counter-terrorism. However, increased vigilance by law enforcement is likely to be a boon for travelers, as scrutiny for unusual activity will be at an all-time high. [UPDATE:] 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: Yes, 0.03 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: No, 0.97 probability 95727ea97c618bc977aed4accfc5b815a782d94f: As things return to a state of normalcy in New Zealand, the likelihood of future terror attacks continually decreases. The government moved quickly to enact new gun laws and even took the extraordinary step of charging people for sharing video of the Christchurch terrorist attacks: https://globalnews.ca/news/5067122/new-zealand-shooting-video-canada-social-media/. This makes it more difficult for the spread of propaganda and hate speech. When you consider the heightened presence of law enforcement and vigilance of local authorities, New Zealand is a fairly safe destination for travelers. Canada's travel advisory for New Zealand hasn't changed: they still want travelers to exercise normal safety precautions when abroad.

question: Before 30 November 2019, will the African Union (AU) lift Sudan's suspension?
rationale: f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: Yes, 0.4 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: No, 0.6 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: Recently, Sudan's opposition factions agreed to start setting up a transitional government. If that holds together, then Sudan may transition to a stable government, which will make it more likely that their membership with the African Union will be reinstated. Of course at this point anything could happen, especially considering that they were suspended for breakdowns in earlier talks that led to violence. [UPDATE:] f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: Yes, 0.6 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: No, 0.4 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: The military and civilian opposition leaders signed a power-sharing agreement just last week. This was seen by some as an attempt to placate the African Union, which has been demanding a shorter timetable for a transition to democracy. There are still some problems, like military control over some Sudanese towns, but it seems like things are headed in the right direction after several violent crackdowns in prior months. [UPDATE:] f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: Yes, 0.6 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: No, 0.4 probability f8690cda838a4857a9d8ffe8b893cf29c4d7d178: It looks like the African Union is taking a "wait and see" attitude toward lifting the suspension. After all, the bloody crackdown on opposition protesters only happened in June. Civilians will hold essentially all the power in the new government https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/time-au-lift-sudan-suspension-190812091743447.html), but only if the constitution is honored by the military during and after the transition. I'm leaving my prediction at the current level.

In June 2018, an outbreak of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 1 (cVDPV1) was declared in Papua New Guinea following laboratory confirmation of cVDPV1 isolation in two healthy communities. Since the declaration, a total of 26 confirmed cVDPV1 cases have been reported in nine provinces.The International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies said recently that the epidemic is fairly under control. question: Before 30 November 2019, will Iran announce they are withdrawing from the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA, or 'Iran nuclear deal')?
rationale: 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: Yes, 0.1 probability 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: No, 0.9 probability 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: It seems very unlikely that Iran will withdraw from the JCPOA. Withdrawal would likely lead to new sanctions from many countries, while remaining in the deal would provide the country with a lot of incentives. The majority of Iranian citizens seem to support the deal, so withdrawing from it would be likely to be a highly unpopular move within the country. Iran's foreign minister Mohammad Javad Zarif has recently said that he will continue to pressure European countries to uphold their commitments and remain in the deal, which shows that withdrawing from JCPOA isn't currently part of Iran's plans. https://en.mehrnews.com/news/143767/Iran-to-keep-pressurizing-Europe-to-fulfill-JCPOA-commitments [UPDATE:] 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: Yes, 0.0 probability 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: No, 1.0 probability 1835d1f63c02b3d62daae6c4f9714c87f4da9dc6: Iran is still under quite a lot of pressure from other countries to stick with the nuclear deal. Since this question began, they have taken some actions that might have violated the JCPOA, but have not made any real moves to withdraw from the agreement. Recently, the U.S. extended sanction waivers for foreign companies working in Iran's nuclear program, effectively keeping one portion of the deal alive despite withdrawing from it over a year ago. Iran's foreign minister Zarif has also called for the U.S. to return to the deal, which gives the impression that the country is still committed to the JCPOA for the time being. It's possible that they might withdraw if they don't get the response they want from the U.S., but if this happens, I doubt that it will happen before 30 November. https://hamodia.com/2019/11/03/irans-zarif-calls-u-s-return-2015-nuclear-deal/

question: Between 30 May 2019 and 29 November 2019, will an Ebola health worker be injured or killed in an attack against an Ebola facility inside the Central African Republic, South Sudan, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi, or Tanzania?
rationale: 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: Yes, 0.3 probability 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: No, 0.7 probability 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: There is a lot of mistrust in that region and people are wary of outsiders. There have been over a hundred attacks on Ebola treatment centers and health workers so far this year in the Congo (https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/05/warns-ebola-breach-drc-borders-attacks-stop-190510185356288.html). While mostly contained to the Congo so far, there is growing risk of the outbreak affecting the above neighboring countries. And some of those countries, like CAF and Sudan, do have a history of attacks on healthcare workers during previous immunization efforts by the WHO (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-health-violence/fights-to-end-polio-contain-ebola-made-tougher-by-rising-violence-research-finds-idUSKCN1SL0BQ). I think with the growing number of cases in the DRC, it's likely the virus spreads into countries on the northeast borders of the DRC. If that happens, there is a good chance of violence against healthcare workers in those countries. But it hasn't happened yet. [UPDATE:] 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: Yes, 0.38 probability 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: No, 0.62 probability 5ee017468becfece17bc8646ca4c3aa3e8dd5d27: Still a long way to go until November but I am going to increase my probability of an attack occurring since the virus has now jumped across the border from the DRC to Uganda. A boy in Uganda has now died and 2 of his relatives have been infected (https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/world/africa/ebola-uganda-congo.html). Depending on whether this gets contained or not, it probably will increase vaccination efforts in that region and this would increase the risk an attack.

question: How many aid workers will have been killed or kidnapped in Afghanistan between January 2019 and November 2019 according to the Aid in Danger (AiD) project?
rationale: 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: Less than 6, 0.4 probability 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: Between 6 and 10, inclusive, 0.5 probability 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: More than 10 but less than 16, 0.1 probability 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: Between 16 and 20, inclusive, 0.0 probability 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: More than 20, 0.0 probability 9c6466d8d8580ce900814e6c7028d845dbc95487: According to a UN report, the most deadly groups in Afghanistan nowadays are actually the government, military and police force (https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/24/politics/united-nations-report-civilians-deaths-afghanistan/index.html). I have a hard time picturing them directly kidnapping aid workers. However, with ISIS losing territory in Iraq and Syria, they have now focused their sights on the increasingly unstable Afghanistan (https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/south-asia/after-caliphate-collapse-isis-militants-head-to-afghanistan-to-plot-attacks). If ISIS can gain an even stronger foothold in the country, all bets are off and aid workers will be in danger. Another wildcard is the Taliban, which is now attempting to become a legitimate political force within Afghanistan (https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/04/afghanistan-peace-deal-depends-taliban-ceasefire-envoy-190428151644299.html). If they decide to go back to their more destructive ways, aid workers will suffer the price. Because of this, I think it's likely that more than 6 will be kidnapped, but unlikely that there will be more than 10 kidnappings.
answer_text: ['Less than 6', 'Between 6 and 10, inclusive', 'More than 10 but less than 16', 'Between 16 and 20, inclusive', 'More than 20']

question: Between 19 September 2019 and 29 November 2019, how many Latin American countries will sign "safe third country" agreements with the United States?
rationale: bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 0, 0.05 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 1, 0.55 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 2, 0.35 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 3 or more, 0.05 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: President Trump has already shown he is willing to make the difficult but necessary steps to curb immigration. The issue is not whether the signing country desires the agreement, but whether or not the US can coerce agreement. In September, foreign aid was drastically cut to Guatemala, Honduras, and El Salvador for failing to address immigration through these nations. Guatemala then quickly signed a safe third country agreement. How long can these other countries survive with reduced US aid? Longer than Guatemala it seems, but probably not much longer. Of course another relevant question is what exactly does the US desire? Mexico has continued to refuse to sign such an agreement but after a tariff scare the nation rapidly deployed new measures to address migrating peoples. But these poorer nations do not have the same means. Instead, the US, with plenty of leverage, will push for this legal framework to accomplish the same goal without having to rely on beleaguered foreign police forces. https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/09/17/761266169/trump-froze-aid-to-guatemala-now-programs-are-shutting-down [UPDATE:] bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 0, 0.0 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 1, 0.0 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 2, 0.95 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: 3 or more, 0.05 probability bc40634ed7c23f191ed59e4704278a0372776ae3: Honduras and El Salvador have now signed such agreements. Along with Guatemala these nations effectively barricade central America. However, many illegal immigrants originate from these countries and therefore may not "pass through" a safe-third country. Thus, Mexico continues to crown jewel of such agreements. But Mexico is adamant that they will not agree and i am not sure how much the administration is really willing to pressure them. Nicaragua and Costa Rica are geographically on the table as well, but relatively fewer illegal immigrants come from nations to the south of these countries. https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-immigration/honduras-to-accept-more-asylum-seekers-under-latest-us-immigration-deal-idUSKBN1WA2QI
